comment.narrative:
1.	Assessment of the current state of biodiversity and ecosystems of the pilot areas and the introduction of sustainable biodiversity management methods;
2.	Expansion of the ecological network to cover the valuable ecosystems of Altai and Saur-Tarbagatai, Western Tien Shan, Dzungarian Alatau, Northern and Central Tien Shan;
3.	Creating a basis for the promotion of joint management and gender equality issues in the project areas
4.	Creating a basis for sustainable management of high conservation value forests in project areas;
5.	Improving the forest fires monitoring system in the project areas;
6.	Introduction of landscape approaches for planning and integrated management of land and forest resources;
7.	Assistance in sustainable development of ecological tourism in pilot PAs
8.	Development of measures to increase the capacity of the inspectors;
9.	Scientific research on the snow leopard population;
10.	Updating the snow leopard monitoring methodology.

1.	Creating a basis for increasing the representativeness of globally significant forest ecosystems of the Northern, Central and Western Tien Shan; 
2.	Improvement of the system of planning and management of pilot PAs;
3.	Improvement of potential and efficiency of activity of pilot PAs; 
4.	Improvement of the system of norms and standards for sustainable forest management and capacity building of forest workers; 
5.	Development and implementation of functional zoning and landscape planning schemes in the pilot areas; 
6.	Sustainable management of forest pastures in the project areas;  
7.	Development of sustainable ecological tourism and introduction of additional ecological education; 
8.	Implementation of effective patrolling approaches using SMART in the pilot PAs; 
9.	Determination of the habitat, assessment of the status of the population of the snow leopard; 
10.	Development of a landscape management plan for the habitat of the snow leopard.

1.	Natural science justifications for expansion of 3 existing PAs (Kolsai Kolderi National Park - 110,000 ha; Zhongar-Alatau National Park - 64,091.4 ha; Karatau Nature Reserve - 22,096.6 ha) and creation of new PA (Merke Regional Park - 74,800.2 ha) were approved. Public hearings on expansion of Karatau Nature Reserve, Kolsai Kolderi National Park and establishment of Merke Regional Nature Park were conducted in the pilot areas with participation of all interested parties; 
2.	In order to implement the new legal provision on the recognition of the Management Plan as a financial planning document, a new Methodology for the development of the PA Management Plan was developed and approved by the Scientific Council of the Committee of Forestry and Wildlife of the MEWR RK. This Methodology has been tested in the development of the Management Plan for 14 pilot PAs for the period 2023-2027; 
3.	Capacity of staff of pilot PAs on planning and budgeting of PAs, as well as on monitoring using quadrocopters has been improved. 
4.	A working group of experts has been formed to develop proposals and recommendations on existing regulations governing the implementation of forest protection measures, measures for forest reproduction and afforestation, management and technical equipment of nature conservation agencies in the fight against forest fires. A capacity building training programme was developed for staff of forest protection institutions, including 18 training modules on sustainable forest management, forest conservation and protection, reforestation, monitoring and others. The programme was approved by the STC of the Committee on Forestry and Wildlife of the MEWR RK. Approbation of the developed Program and modules was conducted in the frames of workshops in October-December 2021, 60 employees of pilot forest enterprises of Almaty and East Kazakhstan regions were covered by the training. 
5.	Draft Schemes of functional zoning of 7 administrative districts of Almaty oblast (Panfilov, Kerbulak, Yeskeldy, Uigur, Rayimbek, Enbekshikazakh, Kegen districts) were developed by applying landscape planning methods. The results of the work identified zones of productive landscapes of agriculture, forestry and hunting farms and elaborated measures for sustainable land use, identified potential ecological corridors for protection of migration routes of key animal species; 
6.	In order to improve the condition of pastures on the example of 4 pilot plots Koksaray , Kaskasu , Belkaragai and Sumbe pilot projects on introduction of sustainable system of pasture turnover and distant pastures are implemented. For improvement of pasture infrastructure 4 sets of yurts with solar panels were purchased, Pasture Management Plan was developed and Public Pasture Councils were established;
7.	In order to raise awareness about the importance of forest ecosystems and biodiversity in the three project areas, a pilot project to develop an additional eco-education programme for grades 6-8 was launched and is being implemented. The pilot project covers more than 100 schools in 5 administrative regions: Katon-Karagai and Kurchum (East Kazakhstan Region), Uigur and Kegen (Almaty Region), and Tolebi (Turkestan Region); 
8.	A SMART-patrolling and monitoring system using the Global Positioning System (GPS) was introduced in 7 pilot institutions. Training sessions on the application of this system in security and monitoring activities were conducted for 300 employees. Field smartphones with accessories (144 pcs.) and external batteries (139 pcs.) were purchased and handed over to the pilot institutions to reinforce the technical equipment of SMART patrolling and monitoring system.
9.	For the first time in Kazakhstan on the territory of Altyn Emel National Park work on satellite telemetry of the snow leopard has started. In this regard, together with the project partners 7 collars and equipment for catching leopards were purchased. The satellite equipment is a collar that sends information about the movements of animals to specialists for further study of migration, identification of threats and development of proposals to minimize them. International experts from the Severtsov Institute with the participation of Kazakh scientists from the Institute of Zoology of the Ministry of Education and Science of Kazakhstan have already conducted telemetry of the female snow leopard.
10.	Snow Leopard Landscape Management Plans have been prepared for the project areas of Western Tien Shan and Altai-Saur. Taking into account the proposal of GSLEP secretariat, the developed documents consist of following sections: analysis of the situation; management issues; conclusion. The management plans are awaiting discussion with the local executive bodies, with the implementing agency.

Component 1.

1. Creation of the basis for increasing the representativeness of globally significant forest ecosystems of the Northern, Central and Western Tien Shan;

2. Improvement of the management system of high conservation value forests;

3. Improvement of the capacity and efficiency of pilot protected areas.

Component 2

4. Development of recommendations to improve the forestry management system;

5. Improvement of the system of norms and standards for sustainable forest management and building capacity of forestry workers;

6. Introduction of landscape approaches for planning and integrated management of land and forest resources;

7. Sustainable management of forest pastures in project areas. 

Component 3

8. Introduction of effective patrol approaches with the use of SMART;

9. Determination of the habitat and assessment of the state of the snow leopard population;

10. Development of a landscape management plan.

Component 1.
1.To increase the coverage of PAs forest ecosystems in 2 project areas, scientific background reports have been prepared on the expansion of 3 pilot PAs and the creation of a new PA (SRNP Merke ) with a total estimated coverage of 270 988 ha. The documents were approved by the Scientific and Technical Council (STC) of the Forestry and Wildlife Committee of the MEGNR of the Republic of Kazakhstan and sent for the state environmental impact assessment. Currently, the feasibility studies are being developed for these PAs, including the preparation of land use design;
2.The Project launched work on updating the Management Plans for 14 pilot PAs in accordance with the new structure approved by the authorized body. A new approach to planning the activities of PAs is based on key values as objects of management and is aimed at mobilizing resources (with strengthening the budget) in PAs based on a clear analysis and building tasks. In this regard, the software for integrated budget planning of PAs (FinPlan) has been developed, which has been tested on the basis of the pilot PAs;
3.The project systematically works to build the human capacity of PAs through trainings and development of Management Plans, a targeted program for monitoring biodiversity, strengthening material and technical equipment, and introducing new SMART technologies. During the reporting period, the following technical support was provided through purchasing of 9 high mobility vehicles, 22 quadcopters and 2 motorboats.
Component 2.
4.To improve forest management within the framework of the Project, for the first time for Kazakhstan, an assessment of the national forest management system is carried out using the international methodology for target scenario analysis (TSA). At the national level was formed an experts working group, 2 missions of international experts to Kazakhstan (study and field) were carried out. Recommendations for sustainable forest management, including optimistic (SEM) and current (BAU) scenarios, will be reviewed in January 2021.
5.•	On the example of 8 pilot forest protection institutions in Almaty and East Kazakhstan regions, the current state and availability of forest fire stations and other equipment was assessed in accordance with the current standards. Based on the results, Recommendations were developed for improving the existing standards for the technical equipment of forest fire stations and proposals for their completion;
6.To ensure the sustainability of knowledge exchange, a training program and 15 thematic training modules are being developed to increase the capacity of forestry employees, including sustainable management, forest protection, reforestation, forest management, climate change, monitoring, etc. At the first stage, the current level of the existing staff of 120 forestry institutions and implemented and current training programs / courses were analyzed, the needs for advanced training identified, and 2 online seminars held;
7.•	The approach and the stages of work on the development of functional zoning of 7 pilot districts of the Almaty region (Panfilov, Kerbulak, Yeskeldy, Uygur, Raiymbek, Yenbekshikazakh and Kegen), the total area of which is 6.0 million hectares, have been determined. A SWOT analysis of the land ecological state, forest and water resources, ecosystems and biodiversity was carried out; existing and potential conflicts in land use, water use and forest use, use of ecosystem services were identified.
The project identified 4 pasture areas: Sumbe, Belkaragay, Kaskasu, Koksaray (total area 58.0 thousand hectares), with a strong degradation where the joint initiatives on sustainable pasture management will be implemented. Together with the partners, the scope of work and contributions were determined, plans for joint work agreed. Within the activities on pastures, it is envisaged to conduct geobotanical studies and determine the norms of grazing, develop pasture Management Plans, create Public Councils, improve infrastructure in distant pastures.
Component 3.
8.The SMART system introduced in the State National Natural Park Sairam-Ugam showed itself effectively. The analysis of the receving data made it possible to improve the patrolling and monitoring scheme. Since March 2020, this National Park has been independently conducting SMART work. SMART was launched in 7 more pilot PAs;
9.Large-scale work on studying habitats, assessing the state of the Kazakhstani population of the snow leopard and its food supply is in progress. Winter, spring-summer, and autumn field studies were carried out. Various methodological techniques were used to collect field data: visual observations, animal tracking, recording traces of life activity and marking activity of the snow leopard. Camera traps were used as the most promising remote method for tracking snow leopards. A gridded approach was used to map snow leopard habitats;
10.The Project is developing two Snow Leopard Landscape Management Plans - Western Tien Shan and Altai-Saur, considering the structural elements proposed by GSLEP. The current state of snow leopard population groups has been studied through field research using camera traps and genetic analysis, the main threats in these landscapes are being identified.
